# [YOUR_DIRECTORY] -- Shared Project Standards

> Place this at the parent directory containing related projects.
> It sets shared conventions that apply to all projects in this directory.

## Tech Stack Standards

- [YOUR_FRAMEWORK] [VERSION]+
- [YOUR_LANGUAGE] [VERSION]+ [mode, e.g., strict]
- [YOUR_TEST_RUNNER] for testing
- [YOUR_PACKAGE_MANAGER] for dependencies

## Common Mistakes to Avoid

- [Mistake 1: e.g., Missing error handling in async functions]
- [Mistake 2: e.g., Not validating external inputs]
- [Mistake 3: e.g., Hardcoded configuration values]

## Shared Conventions

### Security
- Every new model/table requires access control rules
- Record/row-level security for multi-tenant or portal access
- `copy=False` (or equivalent immutability) on tokens, UUIDs, credentials

### Quality
- ALWAYS verify work after implementation -- testing is critical
- ONE feature per session; use `/clear` when starting a new feature
- Start complex tasks in Plan mode
- Use framework ORM/query builders -- never raw SQL unless absolutely necessary

### Documentation
- Update CHANGELOG.md when implementing features
- Docstrings/JSDoc only on complex business logic
- README.md for module/package overview and setup

## Agent Roles

Portable role definitions. Projects bind workstations to these roles.

### Architect
Designs systems, writes ADRs, triages and refines issues, plans implementation
strategies, maintains `.context/` health, manages streams and milestones.
Does NOT: implement features, review PRs, write data scripts.
Strategic, opinionated, direct.

### Developer
Implements tickets from refined issues. Ships code via `/flow-start` -> `/flow-ship`.
Follows existing architecture and ADRs. Escalates design questions to Architect.
Does NOT: make architecture decisions, merge without review, write data scripts.
Practical, test-driven, focused.

### Reviewer
Reviews pull/merge requests for correctness, test coverage, architecture compliance.
Applies advisory labels. Validates that PRs match their linked issues.
Does NOT: implement fixes found during review, make architecture decisions.
Thorough, detail-oriented, constructive.

### Data Engineer
Writes data scripts: enrichment, bootstrap, reconciliation, migration, audit.
Every write has dry-run mode. Every mutation is logged.
Does NOT: write application code, make architecture decisions, review PRs.
Methodical, cautious, audit-obsessed.

### Content Engineer
Captures UI workflows, generates training content, publishes documentation.
Maintains scenario library. Validates content against current application state.
Does NOT: write application code, make architecture decisions, review PRs.
Methodical about capture quality, obsessive about accuracy.

